               <msContents>
                  <summary>I) Taʾāmra ʾIyasus “Miracles of Jesus” (fols. 5ra-97vb)&#xD;
I-1)  Introduction (fols. 5ra-9va) &#xD;
- On John the Evangelist as the author of the book; on creation and the fall of the angel (fols. 5ra-7ra) &#xD;
- Story of the family of Adam (fols. 7ra-9va)&#xD;
I-2) Taʾāmra ʾIyasus “Miracles of Jesus”: 71 miracles (fols. 9va-92va).&#xD;
I-3) Correspondence between King Abgar and Jesus; the story of the martyrs of Akmim (fols. 92va-96va) (ed. S. GRÉBAUT, “Les relations entre Abgar et Jésus”, ROC 21, 1918-19, 73-87; “La mort des martyrs d'Akmim“, ibid. 92-93); a different version of correspondence between King Abgar and Jesus (fols. 96va-97vb) (ed. GETATCHEW HAILE, "The legend of Abgar in Ethiopic Tradition", OrChrP 55, 1989, 375-410, here 378-384)&#xD;
&#xD;
Additio 1.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1">
                     
                     <incipit>
                        <foreign xml:lang="en"/>
                     </incipit>
                     <explicit>
                        <foreign xml:lang="en"/>
                     </explicit>
                     <note/>
                  </msItem>
                  <!--The data in the items below refers to other items. please remove this items and move the information to the appropriate place.-->
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i2">
                     <note>- The second part of Text I-1 is introduced with the word mǝʿrāf “chapter”.</note>
                     <note>- The scribe included in numbering the miracles, the sections of Text I-2.</note>
                     <note>- The miracles are introduced with words taʾammǝr “miracle”, nägär “speech” or mǝʿrāf “chapter”. A few miracles have no particular introductory word.</note>
                     <note>- The first part of Text I-3 is regarded as a part of Text I-2 (with the title taʾammǝr "miracle" and with the number 72)</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
